  "prompt": "Is the activity of money laundering prohibited?",
  "response": "Yes, the activity of money laundering is prohibited and is considered a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legitimate (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illegal funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Concealing the source of the funds through a series of complex transactions.\n3. **Integration**: Making the funds appear to be legitimate by integrating them into the economy.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal because it allows criminals to profit from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism, and it undermines the integrity of financial systems. Governments and international organizations, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), have established laws, regulations, and frameworks to combat money laundering and related activities. Penalties for money laundering can include severe fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences.",
